    <name>
      <text>Finding midpoint between two vectors</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Consider triangle \(PQR\) where \(\vec{PQ} = \mathbf{u}\) and \(\vec{PR} = \mathbf{v}\).</p>
<ul>
    <li>Point \(S\) is located on \(PR\) such that \(PS : SR = {@s1@} : {@s2@}\).</li>
    <li>Point \(T\) lies on \(QR\) with \(QT : TR = {@t1@} : {@t2@}\).</li>
    <li>Point \(U\) is on \(PQ\) such that \(PU : UQ = {@u1@} : {@u2@}\).</li>
</ul>

<p>Determine the following vectors in terms of \(\mathbf{u}\) and \(\mathbf{v}\).</p>
<p><i>(Enter \(\mathbf{u}\) as <code>u</code> and \(\mathbf{v}\) as <code>v</code>).</i></p>

<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>
        \(\vec{PS} = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]
    </li>
    <li>
        \(\vec{PT} = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]
    </li>
    <li>
        \(\vec{PU} = \) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]
    </li>
    <li>
        \(\vec{ST} = \) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]
    </li>
    <li>
        \(\vec{TU} = \) [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]]
    </li>
</ol>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p><b>(a) Finding \(\vec{PS}\)</b></p>
<p>We are given that \(PS : SR = {@s1@} : {@s2@}\). This means the line \(PR\) is divided into \({@s1@} + {@s2@} = {@s_sum@}\) parts.</p>
<p>\(PS\) represents \({@s1@}\) of those parts.</p>
\[ \vec{PS} = \frac{@s1@}{@s_sum@}\vec{PR} = \mathbf{@ta_ps@} \]

<p><b>(c) Finding \(\vec{PU}\)</b></p>
<p>Similarly, \(PU : UQ = {@u1@} : {@u2@}\). The line \(PQ\) is divided into \({@u1@} + {@u2@} = {@u_sum@}\) parts.</p>
\[ \vec{PU} = \frac{@u1@}{@u_sum@}\vec{PQ} = \mathbf{@ta_pu@} \]

<p><b>(b) Finding \(\vec{PT}\)</b></p>
<p>To find \(\vec{PT}\), we first need to travel from \(P\) to \(Q\), and then from \(Q\) to \(T\): \(\vec{PT} = \vec{PQ} + \vec{QT}\).</p>
<p>First, find \(\vec{QR}\):</p>
\[ \vec{QR} = \vec{PR} - \vec{PQ} = \mathbf{v} - \mathbf{u} \]
<p>We know \(QT : TR = {@t1@} : {@t2@}\), so \(QT\) is \(\frac{@t1@}{@t_sum@}\) of \(QR\).</p>
\[ \vec{QT} = \frac{@t1@}{@t_sum@}(\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{u}) \]
<p>Now, add them together:</p>
\[ \vec{PT} = \mathbf{u} + \frac{@t1@}{@t_sum@}(\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{u}) \]
\[ \vec{PT} = \mathbf{@ta_pt_simp@} \]

<p><b>(d) Finding \(\vec{ST}\)</b></p>
<p>Using the triangle rule:</p>
\[ \vec{ST} = \vec{PT} - \vec{PS} \]
\[ \vec{ST} = \left( {@ta_pt_simp@} \right) - \left( {@ta_ps@} \right) \]
\[ \vec{ST} = \mathbf{@ta_st_simp@} \]

<p><b>(e) Finding \(\vec{TU}\)</b></p>
\[ \vec{TU} = \vec{PU} - \vec{PT} \]
\[ \vec{TU} = \left( {@ta_pu@} \right) - \left( {@ta_pt_simp@} \right) \]
\[ \vec{TU} = \mathbf{@ta_tu_simp@} \]]]></text>
